    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bdaa14c3_2ede437a",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T00:08:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s a bit tricky to implement flaky tests this way.\nBecause @computed tracks all the @observables accessed during computation, which does not include variables referenced in callbacks.\nAnd because the yielded variants can be modified when new results are fetched, we need to apply the flakiness filter where those variants are accessed.\nIs it possible to implement that on ResultDB? Since ResultDB is already able to tell variants with unexpected result, I imagine it shouldn\u0027t be hard to implement a VariantWithOnlyUnexpectedResult filter?",
      "parentUuid": "a79cfd4d_83071f6a",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e77bb2b8_c9961c5f",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T06:51:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it is possible but then again, it would mean that merely checking/unchecking checkboxes would cause refetching data that ResultUI already has. It would be slow and unnecessary. \n\nI am also not sure ResultDB would be a good place for this because this problem is specific to ResultUI, so ideally it is solved by ResultUI. For example, we could implement any kind of filtering that you need in resultdb.js with caching. Then even though *this* file would look like a new request to resultdb.js is made, resultdb.js actually reuses the cached response and responds immediately.",
      "parentUuid": "bdaa14c3_2ede437a",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "aedcb27c_803c3130",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:14:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Are results included in different invocations guaranteed to have different variant tags?\nIf not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in the frontend. Because we don\u0027t have all the data. An expected variant may become flaky if we receive an unexpected result in the next page.\nI can implement the flaky filter (in the frontend) in one of the following ways:\n1. implement it in iterator level. Then if a test results become flaky after a new test result page is fetched, it will still present on the page.\n2. implement in in the consumer level. Then if a test results become flaky after a new test result page is fetched, it will disappear from the page (which also means the page no longer always expand in one direction).",
      "parentUuid": "e77bb2b8_c9961c5f",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f98d4227_c433bef1",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:16:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e If not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in the frontend.\n\nIf not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in resultdb.js.",
      "parentUuid": "aedcb27c_803c3130",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0ba587d0_e787236b",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:37:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "good point.\n\nI think (2) is fine here: although it is possible for the same test variant to be in different invocations, this is unlikely, so I expect to very rarely observe appearing/disappearing test variants. \n\nmore context: initally all test variants are sharded into smaller invocations (one test variant runs in one invocation) and those invocations are executed in parallel. In particular, we don\u0027t want to unnecessarily run the same test variant in different invocations because it would be duplication of work. \n\nIf a test is flaky, it is likely to have a mix of expected/unexpected results in the *same* invocation.\n\nNow suppose a test failed 3 times in a row. Currently Chromium recipe has a piece of code that hopes to still get a pass, so it retries the whole invocation. Then all test variants in that invocation are retried. and that previously failed test might pass. This is the case where failures might be in one inv, and pass may be in another, but then again, note that the test fail 3 times before that for this to happen. Note that if it does happen, then with 50% chance, we will see pass before failure because invocations are ordered by their hash in the database (so, random).\n\nfurther, currently rdb incorrectly marks OK results as unexpected, so we see a lot of redness/orangeness in ResultUI. Once that\u0027s fixed, the number of unexpected test results will shrink, so it is likely that all results will fit the first page (1000 results).\n\nAfter all, if it is still a problem, we can further reduce the probability of appearing/disappearing by increasing the page size.",
      "parentUuid": "f98d4227_c433bef1",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6e599044_2461f48d",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T12:17:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I see.\n\n\u003e Now suppose a test failed 3 times in a row. Currently Chromium recipe has a piece of code that hopes to still get a pass, so it retries the whole invocation\n\nOut of curiosity, why do we retry when a test failed 3 times?",
      "parentUuid": "0ba587d0_e787236b",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cdfabf09_732e278a",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T16:56:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "to avoid blocking CLs on flaky tests that were added by other CLs earlier.",
      "parentUuid": "6e599044_2461f48d",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0b60245e_61b78b5d",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1164104
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T20:48:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Driving by 😊 Maybe I have misunderstood something, but I\u0027m not wild about the behavior in (2), what message are we delivering to the users by displaying a flaky as a failure until all the retries are done? Are we encouraging them to investigate the failure? I don\u0027t think that\u0027s the right thing to do because the flake is most likely unrelated to their CL, they shouldn\u0027t be held accountable for that, and given that a flake may randomly affect tons of people, there is a chance that multiple people may start looking into the same flake, which is sub-optimal in terms of resources.\n\nThe reason why there are multiple layers of retries is that, there are some flakes that are dependent on the browser/content_shell\u0027s global state, that said, a test may always fail if you run it individually, but succeed if run a long with an entire test suite.",
      "parentUuid": "cdfabf09_732e278a",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c0ec5a84_e52d7c44",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T21:17:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i agree that we should be clear that an failed test does not necessarily mean that it will stay failed. \nAt this level of abstraction, UI cannot predict whether another test result will appear later. It just displays what it has. I see two coexistent solutions\n- maybe we can more visibly display a banner that this invocation is still not finalized, so more results can be added at any point, also any test variant can be exonerated at any point\n- in the recipe, we can postpone including a task invocation until we know that we won\u0027t be adding more. However, I am not wild about this either because it precludes any streaming.",
      "parentUuid": "0b60245e_61b78b5d",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bfddc222_445c78ea",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1164104
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T21:46:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "streaming is super useful to machines, but I\u0027m really not sure how useful it will be to human in this case, if they know the results may change anyway, most likely, they\u0027ll learn to just ignore the un-finalized results, though one use case I can think of is remote debugging, for those who expect specific tests to fail, streamed early failures are unambiguous to them.\n\nThere are definitely pros and cons, it might be a good idea to talk to a few devs, such as kbr@, jam@ and erikchen@, to learn their expectations.",
      "parentUuid": "c0ec5a84_e52d7c44",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "283e699a_d494cf85",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T22:00:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "makes sense.\n\nto be very clear: whether to report results eagerly or wait until we have a definitive answer is 100% controlled by the recipe owned by EngProd. If it makes more sense not to report eagerly, then let\u0027s not include task invocations into build invocations until the end. Currently this is being done here:\nhttps://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/tools/build/+/master:scripts/slave/recipe_modules/test_utils/api.py;l\u003d339?q\u003dtest_utils%2Fapi.py\nI am OK with both recipe behavior.\n\nif we don\u0027t include eagerly, then we don\u0027t need the banner either. Do I understand correctly that the behavior of code in this CL (which has no idea about what recipe is going to do) is OK with you?",
      "parentUuid": "bfddc222_445c78ea",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
